Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Airways; Sterling Bank Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-09-07T15:55:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-07/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-sterling-bank-nigeria.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
surged 4 percent to 779.02 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, the
biggest increase since May 10, 2010.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index rose for the
first day in three, increasing 0.5 percent to 21,396.43 by the
2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website. Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped four days of
declines, climbing 0.3 percent to 60.20 by the 3 p.m. end of
trading in Nairobi. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose for the first
day in four, gaining 0.1 percent to 1,932.21 as of the 1:30 p.m.
close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
rose less than 0.1 percent to 1,128.56 by the 3 p.m. close in
Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, tumbled 1.25 shillings, or 4.10 percent, to
29.25 shillings, the lowest close since Nov. 19, 2009. Kenya’s
Treasury cut by more than half the funds allocated to Kenya
Airways’s planned $250 million rights offer, Business Daily
reported, citing an official it didn’t identify.  Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender snapped
two days of declines, advancing 5 kobo, or 3.7 percent, to 1.4
naira, the biggest gain since Aug. 24. Equatorial Trust Bank
Plc’s shareholders and board approved the lender’s acquisition
by Sterling Bank, ThisDay reporter, citing Managing Director
Gbolahan Folayan.  To contact the reporter on this story:
